<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Red Centre Way</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Red Centre Way</h2><p><i>Northern Territory, Australia · Alice Springs loop via Kings Canyon and Uluru</i></p><p><b>1,135 km loop through the geographic heart of Australia — West MacDonnells, Kings Canyon, Uluru, Kata Tjuta.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>1022 km (635 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–6 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–September (summer heat is dangerous)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Mereenie Loop is unsealed and rough — 4WD recommended; permits required for parts of the loop crossing Aboriginal land; extreme heat; flies</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>1237</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Red Centre is older than almost anywhere else on Earth — the MacDonnell Ranges are the eroded roots of mountains once Himalayan in scale, ground down over 350 million years to the spinifex-covered ridges that remain. Uluru and Kata Tjuta are not the same rock as the surrounding desert; both are inselbergs ('island mountains') of conglomerate and sandstone, with their bases buried in 5 km of red sand. The Anangu people, the traditional owners, have lived in this country for at least 30,000 years and continuously since. Climbing Uluru was permanently closed in October 2019 in deference to Anangu wishes; respect that, and the experience of walking the 10 km base loop at sunrise is the better one anyway.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Standley Chasm</b> — 9 m-wide gorge that lights up an extraordinary orange for ~30 minutes around midday when the sun reaches the floor. Aboriginal-owned. Small entry fee.</li><li><b>Ormiston Gorge</b> — Permanent waterhole flanked by 250 m red walls. 7 km Pound Walk loops up and around — superb. Black-footed rock wallabies on the cliff above the parking lot.</li><li><b>Tnorala / Gosse Bluff</b> — 5 km-wide circular ridge — the eroded core of a comet impact 142 million years ago. Sacred to Western Arrernte people; restricted areas inside the crater.</li><li><b>Kings Canyon</b> — 270 m sheer red walls. The 6 km Rim Walk is one of Australia's great hikes — climb the steep first 100 m at dawn and the reward is everything that follows. The Garden of Eden waterhole at the canyon head.</li><li><b>Uluru</b> — 348 m sandstone monolith, rising from a desert plain that was once an inland sea. 10 km base walk; sunrise viewing area is on the east side; ranger-led Mala Walk explains Anangu Tjukurpa (Law/Dreaming).</li><li><b>Kata Tjuta (The Olgas)</b> — 36 conglomerate domes rising to 546 m — taller than Uluru and visible from it. The Valley of the Winds walk (7 km loop) goes deep among them; closed by 11 AM if temperatures exceed 36 °C.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
